First, we can simplify the expression inside each square root:

\begin{align*}
\sqrt{5+\sqrt{21}}&=\sqrt{5+3\sqrt{7}}\\
\sqrt{5-\sqrt{21}}&=\sqrt{5-3\sqrt{7}}
\end{align*}

Next, we can use the fact that $\sqrt{a+b} = \sqrt{a}\sqrt{\frac{b+\sqrt{b^2+4ac}}{2c}}$ to simplify each expression further:

\begin{align*}
\sqrt{5+3\sqrt{7}}&=\sqrt{\frac{(3\sqrt{7})^2+4(1)(5)}{2(1)}}\\
\sqrt{5-3\sqrt{7}}&=\sqrt{\frac{(-3\sqrt{7})^2+4(1)(5)}{2(1)}}
\end{align*}

Now, we can simplify the expression further:

\begin{align*}
\sqrt{5+3\sqrt{7}}&=\sqrt{\frac{9\cdot 7 + 20}{2}}\\
\sqrt{5-3\sqrt{7}}&=\sqrt{\frac{9\cdot 7 - 20}{2}}
\end{align*}

To simplify the expression further, we can use the fact that $\sqrt{a} = \pm x$ where $x^2=a$. In this case:

\begin{align*}
\sqrt{5+3\sqrt{7}}&=\frac{\sqrt{(9\cdot 7 + 20)/2}}{\sqrt{1}}\\
\sqrt{5-3\sqrt{7}}&=\frac{-\sqrt{(9\cdot 7 - 20)/2}}{\sqrt{1}}
\end{align*}

Now, we can add the two expressions together:

$$\sqrt{5+3\sqrt{7}} + \sqrt{5-3\sqrt{7}} = \frac{\sqrt{(9\cdot 7 + 20)/2} - \sqrt{(9\cdot 7 - 20)/2}}{\sqrt{1}}$$

To evaluate this expression, we can use a calculator or equation solver.

